T1  - ENTRY ORDER, PERFORMANCE, AND GEOGRAPHY: THE CASE OF THE CONVENIENCE-STORE INDUSTRY IN JAPAN
AU  - Nishida, Mitsukuni
Y1  - 2025/05/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12742
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 787
EP  - 822
VL  - 66
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12742
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - Abstract Entry-order effects on economic profits have not been extensively studied due to data limitations. This article empirically examines these effects on revenues and costs using a structural approach without requiring information on accounting profits and costs. Utilizing panel data from Japan's convenience-store industry, I apply a two-step estimator for many geographic markets. The results reveal that whereas early entrants gain 4.8% more revenue at the outlet level, subsequent entrants benefit from a 7.6% and 5.8% reduction in variable and expansion costs. Simulations suggest initial benefits from delayed entry, but these may dissipate over time, particularly in rapidly growing markets.
ER  - 

